. You miss my point. If you look at the drawables themselves, some have excess space around them, inside the drawable. This is where the inconsistency creeps in.
Here are some examples. (All icons below are nominally 24dp, ie. the image in drawable-mdpi is physically 24px x 24px. The physical icon I refer to is the rectangular region within the image that actually contains non-transparent pixels.)
- ic_inbox_grey600_24dp.png has 3dp of padding; the actual physical icon is 18dp high and 18dp wide.
- ic_cloud_upload_grey600_24dp.png has no padding; the actual physical icon is 16dp high and 24dp wide.
- ic_send_grey600_24dp.png has 1dp of padding; the actual physical icon is 18dp high and 21dp wide (with 2dp padding on left and 1dp padding on right).
- ic_delete_grey600_24dp.png has 3dp of padding; the actual physical icon is 18dp high and 14dp wide.
The corresponding IIcons use the same physical icon shapes but don't retain the padding. This means that when actually using the above four icons in a navigation drawer (as I am), ic_inbox and ic_delete appear much larger than they should.
Yes, your drawer is correctly implementing the Material Design Guidelines for navigation drawer icons. But the IIcons themselves are inconsistently sized, which leads to the drawer IIcons being incorrectly sized. So if allowing the IIcons to be resized here is the wrong solution, then the right one is for the IIcons to correctly include the padding that they are supposed to.
. I can, yes. I have now had a chance to test the padding methods, and it does solve the problem this issue covers. However, I still think it shouldn't be necessary for every single developer to manually measure and apply this padding just to re-instate the right inter-icon ratios.
Thinking about it, this is probably a more general Android-Iconics issue. Perhaps having e.g. a GoogleMaterial.PaddedIcon class that automatically adds the original padding (and then the user can add extra padding with paddingDp() to that as they need) would be the best way to resolve this.
. I can, yes. I have now had a chance to test the padding methods, and it does solve the problem this issue covers. However, I still think it shouldn't be necessary for every single developer to manually measure and apply this padding just to re-instate the right inter-icon ratios.
Thinking about it, this is probably a more general Android-Iconics issue. Perhaps having e.g. a GoogleMaterial.PaddedIcon class that automatically adds the original padding (and then the user can add extra padding with paddingDp() to that as they need) would be the best way to resolve this.
. Or alternatively, a new icon namespace could be added - gmdp - that uses all the gmd icons but includes their original padding. This would be far more versatile and useful to developers, and I expect probably easier to implement.
