. @mikepenz So it TOTALLY was Firebase. Here's the problem for anyone finding this:
- I had followed the Firebase Auth tutorial that showed to register the OnAuthenticationChangeListener during OnStart and release during OnStop.
- In my OnAuthenticationChangeListener I had a call to my own remote server API for user interaction. The result of this API would update the account header. 
- The registered activity's registration causes OnAuthenticationChangeListener to fire during OnPause of the original activity.
My solutiuon: I used the Firebase-UI library to handle the firebase account selection options: https://github.com/firebase/FirebaseUI-Android/blob/master/auth/README.md
I removed the listener from the activity and only had it fire during OnCreate of that activity only. This prevents the half-loading, random fire of the auth-chain that was messing everything up. This is described in the link above. Here's the onCreate that handles the firebase user checking. @mikepenz Thanks for your help, I think it's safe to close this now (thanks firebase...).  I'll create a demo if anyone thinks it'll help??? 
     @Override
protected void onCreate(@Nullable Bundle savedInstanceState) {
    super.onCreate(savedInstanceState);
    if (FirebaseAuth.getInstance().getCurrentUser() == null)
        needsLogin();
    else
        Firebase.getCurrentInstance()
                .getCurrentUser()
                .getToken(true)
                .addOnSuccessListener(new OnSuccessListener<GetTokenResult>() {
                    @Override
                    public void onSuccess(GetTokenResult getTokenResult) {
                        confirmFirebaseAisUser("Null", getTokenResult.getToken());
                    }
                })
                .addOnFailureListener(new OnFailureListener() {
                    @Override
                    public void onFailure(@NonNull Exception e) {
                        onAuthenticationError(e);
                    }
                });
}

